id="post-4243" class="post-4243 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-energy tag-spain tag-sustianable tag-wind"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/01/21/wind-becomes-largest-source-of-energy-in-spain/" title="Permalink to Wind Becomes Largest Source of Energy in Spain" rel="bookmark">Wind Becomes Largest Source of Energy in Spain</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2014/01/21 3:59 pm"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/01/21/wind-becomes-largest-source-of-energy-in-spain/" title="Wind Becomes Largest Source of Energy in Spain" rel="bookmark">2014/01/21 3:59 pm</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="comments-link"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/01/21/wind-becomes-largest-source-of-energy-in-spain/#comments">Leave a Comment</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>Spain makes use of a plethora of energy sources and they are leaders in Europe when it comes to utilizing solar and wind energy. Energy policy is always under debate in the country and hopefully they will continue their overall trend of helping sustainable energy develop.</p><blockquote><p>Wind accounted for 20.9 percent of the country’s energy last year — more than any other enough to power about 15.5 million households, with nuclear coming in a very close second at 20.8 percent. Wind energy usage was up over 13 percent from the year before, according to the report.</p><p>The news is being hailed by environmental advocates as a sign that Spain, and perhaps the rest of the world, is ready for a future based on renewables. But the record comes at the end of a very rocky year for Spain’s renewable energy sector, which was destabilized by subsidy cutbacks and arguments over how much the government should regulate renewable energy companies.</p><p>Despite the flaws in Spain’s system, the numbers are promising for green energy fans. The renewable push brought down Spain’s greenhouse gas emissions by 23 percent, according to another industry report from Red Electric Espana (REE).</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/1/16/spain-becomes-firstcountrytorelymostlyonwindforenergy.html">Read more.</a></p><div
class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-1111807-4243-53835c40b82d1' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/#blog_id=1111807&amp;post_id=4243&amp;origin=www.thingsaregood.com&amp;obj_id=1111807-4243-53835c40b82d1' data-name='like-post-frame-1111807-4243-53835c40b82d1'><h3 class='sd-title'>Like this:</h3><div
